<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>CBRWS v1 Link Relations</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
</head>
<body>
<header>
  <h1>CBRWS v1 Link Relations</h1>
  <p>
    URL: <code>{{ relations_directory_url }}</code>
  </p>
</header>

<main>
  <section>
    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <p>{{ description }}</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Where This Page Fits</h2>
    <p>
      This page sits inside the v1 CBRWS schema in the URL hierarchy
      of this web service. (In this documentation the word
      <em>endpoint</em> means a URL that responds to HTTP requests;
      the two terms are used interchangeably.)
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws/v1</code> &mdash; the v1 API schema.
        It describes the response returned by <code>/api</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws/v1/rels</code> &mdash; <strong>this
        page</strong>. It lists the custom <em>link relations</em>
        that appear in responses from the v1 API.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>/profiles/cbrws/v1/rels/{rel}</code> &mdash; the
        documentation for a single link relation named
        <code>{rel}</code>. Each entry in the
        <a href="#directory-contents">Directory Contents</a> table
        below is one of these pages.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What Is a "Link Relation"?</h2>
    <p>
      When the v1 API returns a JSON response, the response contains
      a block called <code>_links</code>. Each entry in
      <code>_links</code> is keyed by a short name and points to
      another URL. The short name is called a <em>link relation</em>.
      It tells the client <em>why</em> a link is there &mdash; what
      the linked resource is in relation to the current one. For
      example, the relation <code>self</code> points back to the URL
      of the response itself, and the relation <code>cbrws:greeting</code>
      points to the greeting endpoint.
    </p>
    <p>
      Some relation names are standardized (like <code>self</code>,
      <code>next</code>, <code>up</code>). The ones this API defines
      for itself are called <em>custom</em> relations and are listed
      on this page.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The <code>cbrws:</code> Prefix and the <code>{rel}</code> Template</h2>
    <p>
      Custom relation names must be globally unique, so in principle
      each one should be a full URL. To keep responses readable,
      HAL lets the server publish a short prefix (a <em>CURIE</em>,
      short for Compact URI) that expands to a URL template. In this
      API the prefix is <code>cbrws</code>, and its template is:
    </p>
    <pre><code>{{ curie_href_template }}</code></pre>
    <p>
      The <code>{rel}</code> part is a placeholder. To get the full
      URL for a relation, substitute the relation's short name for
      <code>{rel}</code>. For example, the relation written in a
      response as <code>cbrws:greeting</code> expands to:
    </p>
    <pre><code>{{ greeting_relation_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>
      Fetching that URL returns the documentation page for the
      <code>cbrws:greeting</code> relation &mdash; that is what every
      entry in the table below is. The <code>{rel}</code> syntax
      itself comes from a standard called RFC 6570, which describes
      how placeholders inside URL templates are filled in.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="directory-contents">
    <h2>Directory Contents</h2>
    <p>The following custom link relations are defined by the v1 API:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Relation</th>
          <th>URL</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>cbrws:greeting</code></td>
          <td>
            <a href="{{ greeting_relation_url }}"><code>{{ greeting_relation_url }}</code></a>
          </td>
          <td>
            Documentation for the link that points from the
            discovery endpoint to the greeting endpoint. Open the
            URL in a browser for the human-readable page, or
            request it with
            <code>Accept: application/schema+json</code> to fetch
            the machine-readable JSON Schema for the greeting
            response.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Content Negotiation</h2>
    <p>
      This directory page is itself available in two formats. Which
      one you receive depends on the <code>Accept</code> header in
      your request:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th><code>Accept</code> Header</th>
          <th>What You Get</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <code>application/hal+json</code> (or omitted)
          </td>
          <td>
            A JSON document listing the custom link relations as
            navigable links. This is the default and is intended for
            programs that walk the API automatically. (HAL is a
            convention for embedding navigation links inside JSON
            under a key named <code>_links</code>; the rest of the
            document is ordinary JSON.)
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>text/html</code> (or a browser)</td>
          <td>This human-readable page.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Examples using curl:</p>
    <pre><code># Fetch the machine-readable HAL+JSON directory
curl -s -H "Accept: application/hal+json" {{ relations_directory_url }}

# Fetch the human-readable HTML page
curl -s -H "Accept: text/html" {{ relations_directory_url }}</code></pre>
  </section>
</main>

